<span class="displaytext"><b><em>sen. (candidate last) voted against the bush tax cuts; candidate (candidate last) supports them</em></b> <p><b> <em>"anybody who watched my campaign should not have been astounded that i voted against the [bush] tax cut ..."</em> – sen. (candidate full), 2001</b> (kirk victor, "(candidate last)'s evolution," <em>national journal</em>, 8/8/01) </p><p><b> <em>"i will not let the (PARTY NAME) roll back the bush tax cuts."</em> – sen. (candidate full), 2007</b> (liz sidoti, "(candidate last): retool jobs programs," <em>the associated press</em>, 10/10/07) </p><p><b> <u> on the campaign trail, sen. (candidate last) now pledges to make the bush tax cuts permanent:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last)'s economic plan calls for making the bush tax cuts permanent.</b> "(candidate full) will make the bush income and investment tax cuts permanent, keeping income tax rates at their current level and fighting the (PARTY NAME)' plans for a crippling tax increase in 2011. left to their devices, (PARTY NAME) will impose a massive $100 billion tax hike, almost $700 per taxpayer every year." (sen. (candidate full), "(candidate full) unveils economic plan: bold solutions for american prosperity," press release, 12/18/07) </p><p><b> <u>but in the senate, (candidate last) voted against the bush tax cuts, saying they benefited the wealthy:</u> </b> </p><p><b>in 2001, sen. (candidate last) was one of only two (PARTY NAME)s to vote against the $1.35 trillion bush tax cuts.</b> the bill lowered marginal rates, eliminated the marriage penalty, and doubled the child tax credit. (h.r. 1836, cq vote #170: adopted 58-33: r 46-2; d 12-31; i 0-0, 5/26/01, (candidate last) voted nay) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- sen. (candidate last) said the 2001 bush tax cuts benefited the wealthy.</b> sen. (candidate full): "i think there is a belief in america that too much of this tax cut still goes to wealthiest americans. and maybe we could do something about those that still pay a significant portion of their income in payroll taxes." (cnn's "late edition," 3/11/01) </p></blockquote> <p><b>in 2003, sen. (candidate last) was one of only three (PARTY NAME)s to twice vote against the $350 billion bush tax cuts.</b> the comprehensive bill lowered taxes by $350 billion over 11 years - including increasing the child tax credit and elminating the marriage penality. (h.r. 2, cq vote #179: passed 51-49: r 48-3; d 3-45; i 0-1, 5/15/03, (candidate last) voted nay; h.r. 2, cq vote #196: adopted 50-50: r 48-3; d 2-46; i 0-1, 5/23/03, (candidate last) voted nay) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- sen. (candidate last) said the 2003 bush tax cuts benefited the wealthy.</b> (candidate last): "i want to see tax cuts, if they are necessary, go to working americans, not the wealthiest." (richard ruelas, "(candidate last) isn't saying 'oui' to bush's tax cut plan," <em>the arizona republic</em>, 4/25/03) </p></blockquote> <p><b> <u>and in 2004, sen. (candidate last) said he was against making all of the bush tax cuts permanent:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate full): "they want to make the tax cuts for higher-income people permanent, and i don't want that."</b> (npr's "morning edition," 6/16/04) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) said he would "clearly" not support extending the tax cuts.</b> nbc's tim russert: "since the civil war, every president who has been at war has increased taxes. should the president consider postponing his tax cut?" sen. (candidate last): "i would have – i voted against the tax cuts because of the disproportionate amount that went to the wealthiest americans. i would clearly support not extending those tax cuts in order to help address the deficit. but the middle-income tax credits, the families, the child tax credits, the marriage tax credits, all of those i would keep." (nbc's "meet the press," 4/11/04) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last): "i don't think we should continue to cut taxes."</b> (candidate last): "i don't think we should continue to cut taxes. i like – i think every american – i'm in favor of the middle-class, middle- income tax cuts, and i would vote to make them permanent." (sen. (candidate full), remarks, washington, d.c., 5/18/04)</p></span>



